      Apes vs. APEs
   =20
 =20

You   know the   deal. AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. had a meme stock tha=
t traded up a lot even as AMC=E2=80=99s business was struggling. AMC took a=
dvantage of this dynamic to sell a lot of stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0so much stoc=
k, in fact, that it ran out. Its corporate charter authorizes 524 million c=
ommon shares, and by last summer it had issued essentially all of them.=C2=
=A0
The obvious solution was for AMC to ask its shareholders to vote to amend t=
he charter and authorize more shares. In 2021, AMC did that, but then withd=
rew the proposal in the face of shareholder =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, I am not s=
ure what to call it. =E2=80=9CShareholder opposition,=E2=80=9D perhaps. =E2=
=80=9CShareholder indifference,=E2=80=9D maybe. The point is that AMC neede=
d to get a vote of a majority of all of its common shares to approve the ch=
arter amendment. There were two problems. One is that its shareholders are =
mostly individual retail investors, and retail investors tend not to vote m=
uch
  [1]
;=C2=A0only about half of AMC=E2=80=99s shares voted at its  last annual me=
eting. The other is that some of those investors really didn=E2=80=99t like=
 the plan to issue more stock, worrying that it would dilute their ownershi=
p (or help out short sellers, or otherwise bring down the price of AMC stoc=
k). Those two problems are additive: AMC needed a majority of=C2=A0all=C2=
=A0of its shares to vote to authorize more shares; if 40% of its shareholde=
rs didn=E2=80=99t vote and another 20% voted no, then the proposal would fa=
il. So AMC  withdrew it.=C2=A0
Last summer, AMC came up with a   less obvious but much funnier solution: I=
ts board used its authority to issue =E2=80=9Cblank-check preferred stock=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0basically preferred stock with any terms it likes,=
 without shareholder approval =E2=80=94=C2=A0to issue a new sort of stock c=
alled APEs, AMC Preferred Equity Units, that are meant to replicate common =
stock. They have the same economic rights as common stock, and the same vot=
ing rights. AMC airdropped the APEs on its shareholders, issuing one APE fo=
r each common share as a stock dividend, and then went merrily along sellin=
g APEs to raise more cash.
One way for this to go would be for the market to decide that APEs are a cl=
ose substitute for common shares, and price them accordingly. That mostly d=
id not happen: By Dec. 21, AMC=E2=80=99s common stock was trading at $5.30 =
per share, while the APEs were at just $0.685. AMC was selling an economic =
equivalent to common stock at an 80+% discount to the price of the common s=
tock, which is=C2=A0definitely=C2=A0dilutive for shareholders.
The other way for it to go would be for AMC to ask shareholders again to am=
end the charter and authorize more shares, and then to use the additional a=
uthorization to convert the APEs into common shares and collapse everything=
 back into one, more abundant, class of stock. On Dec. 22, AMC=C2=A0announc=
ed=C2=A0that it would do that. The APEs went up, and the common stock went =
down, as the market anticipated that the conversion.
The shareholder vote to approve the conversion is  scheduled for March 14. =
One assumes it will be approved:
=09The APEs and common shares vote together as a single class, and there ar=
e now way more APEs than common shares.=09The APEs have an incentive to vot=
e yes: If their APEs are converted into common stock, that is good for APE =
holders, since right now APEs trade at a much lower price than the common.=
=09A big block of APEs was placed with one investor, Antara Capital LP, who=
 agreed to hold its APEs through the vote and vote them in favor of the ame=
ndment.=09The APEs have a voting mechanism where they are technically prefe=
rred shares held by a depositary, and the depositary has to vote=C2=A0all=
=C2=A0of the shares in proportion to the voting instructions it actually ge=
ts, so if 40% of APE holders vote yes and 10% vote no (and 50% don=E2=80=99=
t vote), the actual preferred shares will vote 80% yes and 20% no.

I   wrote: =E2=80=9CAMC has solved the problem of retail non-voting, by giv=
ing its retail shareholders APE units that (1) have voting rights but (2) d=
on=E2=80=99t rely on most of the holders actually bothering to vote.=E2=80=
=9D
Then   some shareholders sued, claiming that this is all not allowed, that =
it is a trick to get around the requirement that the board can=E2=80=99t am=
end the charter without the approval of a majority of all shares. (Which is=
 true!) And yesterday they  struck a deal with AMC:=C2=A0
=09The vote will go ahead as scheduled on March 14.=09AMC will report how m=
any common shares vote for the proposal, how many vote against, how many do=
n=E2=80=99t vote, etc., and also how many APEs do each of those things.=09W=
hether or not AMC wins the vote =E2=80=94=C2=A0again, I expect it will win =
the=C2=A0overall=C2=A0vote =E2=80=94=C2=A0it will not immediately amend the=
 charter to authorize more shares; instead it will wait for a court hearing=
.=09They=E2=80=99ll meet back in court on April 27 to fight over whether AM=
C can amend the charter.

The result is that, when they go to court to decide if all of this is fair =
or not, they=E2=80=99ll=C2=A0know what the vote was. Conceptually:
=09If everyone votes no, then AMC won=E2=80=99t amend the charter and the l=
awsuit will be irrelevant.=09If a majority of all of the common shares vote=
 yes, and the APEs also vote yes, then that will be a pretty strong indicat=
ion that this is all fine and shareholders approve it anyway, so the lawsui=
t will probably be irrelevant.=09If a majority of the common shares=C2=A0th=
at vote=C2=A0vote yes, and the APEs also vote yes, but the amendment fails =
to get a majority of=C2=A0all=C2=A0of the common shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0if 4=
0% of the common votes yes, 20% votes no, and 40% doesn=E2=80=99t vote at a=
ll, say =E2=80=94=C2=A0then in April AMC will have a decent argument to the=
 judge to the effect of: =E2=80=9CLook, yes, we did this to get around the =
strict letter of the=C2=A0voting requirements, but as you see, even with al=
l the publicity this has generated, our shareholders never vote. So we are =
doing what we think is best for them and also what a majority of them, as b=
est we can tell, actually want.=E2=80=9D I am not=C2=A0sure=C2=A0that a jud=
ge would allow the amendment, in this case, but it would be a bit harsh to =
stop it.=09Conversely, if a majority of the APEs vote yes, and if that is e=
nough for the amendment to pass, but most of the=C2=A0common=C2=A0sharehold=
ers who vote=C2=A0vote no, then the suing shareholders will have a decent a=
rgument to the judge of to the effect of: =E2=80=9CLook, AMC did this with =
the intention of avoiding shareholder approval, and the shareholders =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the real, common shareholders =E2=80=94 voted against it, but they=
 want to do it anyway, and you shouldn=E2=80=99t let them.=E2=80=9D I am no=
t=C2=A0sure=C2=A0that a judge would stop the amendment, in this case, but i=
t would be pretty sticky.

But I don=E2=80=99t know what will happen and the nice thing is that we=E2=
=80=99ll find out in March. And then if it=E2=80=99s Outcome 1 or Outcome 2=
, the lawsuit is irrelevant; if it=E2=80=99s Outcome 3, AMC=E2=80=99s chanc=
es in court will be pretty good; if it=E2=80=99s Outcome 4, AMC=E2=80=99s c=
hances will be much worse.
By the way. I don=E2=80=99t know what would have happened if AMC had actual=
ly held a vote to authorize more shares in July 2021, when it had planned t=
o. One possibility is that the amendment would have passed, narrowly. Anoth=
er is that it would have failed because most shareholders would have voted =
against it. A third possibility =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps the most likely? =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0is that it would have gotten more yes votes than no votes, but =
not=C2=A0enough=C2=A0yes votes; it would have gotten a majority of the=C2=
=A0votes=C2=A0but not of the total=C2=A0shares, and would fail. And if that=
 had happened, then AMC could have eventually done the APEs thing, and then=
 it could go to a judge now and say =E2=80=9Clook, our shareholders want th=
is, but they don=E2=80=99t vote, so we found a way to do it for them anyway=
,=E2=80=9D and the judge might be sympathetic.
One reason I think this was the most likely outcome is because AMC clearly =
should have been issuing stock in July 2021, when the stock was trading in =
the $40s and AMC was a $20 billion company; the stock closed yesterday at $=
7.61, for a market cap under $6 billion. Surely not every AMC shareholder s=
aw it that way =E2=80=94=C2=A0if they were buying the stock at $40 I guess =
they thought it was worth more =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, I mean, it was a really =
good opportunity to sell stock.
But=C2=A0now=C2=A0things are different.=C2=A0Now, if=C2=A0you are an AMC co=
mmon shareholder, you might reasonably vote no on this proposal:
=09The stock is cheaper now, so share issuances will be more dilutive.=09In=
 particular, converting the APEs into common stock will be dilutive: Antara=
 bought more than  250 million APEs for under $1 each, and would now get to=
 convert them into common stock that=C2=A0closed yesterday at $7.61.=09You =
might just be mad at AMC for trying to sneak this past you.

You might still reasonably vote yes! You might think, well, yes, AMC does n=
eed to raise equity capital, so we=E2=80=99d better let them. You might thi=
nk, well, if we don=E2=80=99t approve the amendment, they=E2=80=99re going =
to keep issuing APEs at under $1 per share, and that=E2=80=99s worse than j=
ust selling common stock. But in July 2021, it would have been reasonable t=
o say =E2=80=9Clook, our shareholders=C2=A0should=C2=A0want to authorize mo=
re shares, and they probably=C2=A0do, but they just don=E2=80=99t vote.=E2=
=80=9D Now that is much less obvious. Now they might actually vote no. Whic=
h would make AMC=E2=80=99s argument in court a lot harder.
Anyway this deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0vote in March, but wait until April for the=
 court hearing =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems to be good for the common stock price a=
nd bad for the APE price. It is particularly=C2=A0terrible for anyone who i=
s in the arbitrage trade of being long the APEs, short the common, and bett=
ing on convergence. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Yiqin Shen and Bailey Lipshultz   r=
eported yesterday:

AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. common stock surged 23% after a Delaware co=
urt said it will hold a preliminary injunction hearing on April 27, signali=
ng a highly anticipated conversion between the shares and preferred units m=
ay take longer than expected. =E2=80=A6
The common stock spiked to $7.61 while APE shares slipped to $2.05. =E2=80=
=A6
=E2=80=9CThe preliminary injunction hearing on April 27 extends the time th=
at investors have to hold long APE/short AMC by at least a month and a half=
, given the horrifically high cost of borrow this is a painful outcome for =
arbitragers,=E2=80=9D said Cabot Henderson, who focuses on merger arbitrage=
 and special situations at JonesTrading.


