      Tilray
   =20
 =20

Maybe a clearer situation is Tilray. Tilray Brands Inc. is a meme-y cannabi=
s company (equity market capitalization $9.6 billion in June 2021, $1.7 bil=
lion yesterday) with, naturally, a very retail investor base. Tilray has ha=
d some trouble getting shareholders to vote to approve stuff, not because t=
hey don=E2=80=99t like the stuff but because they are retail shareholders a=
nd don=E2=80=99t vote. In 2021, it  had trouble getting shareholders to vot=
e to approve a =E2=80=9Ccannabis megamerger.=E2=80=9D Not that they don=E2=
=80=99t love a cannabis megamerger, but as Tilray=E2=80=99s CEO said:
"It's hard to get those shareholders to show up and vote," Simon said. "You=
 know, nobody has home phones anymore. No one answers their cellphone to an=
 unknown number. When you mail a proxy to someone's house or apartment, it =
goes in the garbage."
Ultimately=C2=A037.7% of shares voted in favor of the merger and just 0.8% =
voted against: overwhelming approval, but not a majority of all the shares.=
 The deal closed anyway, because Tilray did not actually need a majority of=
 all of its shares to approve the merger.
But Tilray, like AMC, would also like to amend its charter to authorize mor=
e shares, and that does=C2=A0require a majority.=C2=A0In fact Tilray=C2=A0d=
id=C2=A0get a majority of shares to vote to increase its authorized shares =
in June 2021, but just barely; 227 million of the 449 million shares then o=
utstanding voted yes. (About 33 million voted no.)
Now it wants to do it again. Now it has about 615 million shares outstandin=
g, out of about 746.7 million authorized shares. Technically these are all =
its =E2=80=9CClass 2=E2=80=9D shares; its charter authorizes 233 million su=
per-voting =E2=80=9CClass 1=E2=80=9D shares, but those are no longer outsta=
nding. Tilray would like to amend its charter to eliminate the dual class s=
hares and collapse everything into 980 million authorized common shares, wh=
ich would have two advantages. One is that there=E2=80=99d be neater, bette=
r governance, with no super-voting stock and no confusing references to it =
in the charter. Here=E2=80=99s  what Tilray says:
Our Board believes that our Certificate of Incorporation as currently in ef=
fect may confuse stockholders, the investing public and other third parties=
 because of references to our Class 1 common stock. Among other things, eli=
minating these references will help to prevent any mistaken belief on the p=
art of the investing public or others who report on or follow our publicly-=
traded equity securities that we may have another outstanding class of comm=
on equity. In addition, the Board believes that there should be no Class 1 =
common shares with supermajority voting rights. Instead, each share of the =
Company=E2=80=99s common stock should have one vote per share.
The other advantage is, of course, more (regular) common stock to issue if =
Tilray needs to.
Inspired by all the other weird preferred stock deals, Tilray is doing one.=
 It  announced last week:

Tilray Brands, Inc. (=E2=80=9CTilray Brands=E2=80=9D or the =E2=80=9CCompan=
y=E2=80=9D) (NASDAQ | TSX: TLRY), a leading global cannabis-lifestyle and c=
onsumer packaged goods company, today announced that the Company has entere=
d into an agreement for the issuance of 120,000 shares of Series A Preferre=
d Stock (the =E2=80=9CSeries A Preferred Stock=E2=80=9D).
The Series A Preferred Stock is entitled to 1,000 votes per share, but may =
only vote on the Company=E2=80=99s pending proposal to eliminate Tilray Bra=
nd=E2=80=99s Class 1 Common Stock (=E2=80=9CProposal 3=E2=80=9D). Proposal =
3, if approved, would eliminate the unissued Class 1 Common Stock by reclas=
sifying it into shares of the Company=E2=80=99s authorized and unissued Cla=
ss 2 Common Stock.=C2=A0
The Series A Preferred Stock cannot vote independently, but instead must vo=
te in the same proportion (For or Against) as all shares of Class 2 Common =
Stock are voted. The Series A Preferred Stock will convert automatically to=
 Class 2 Common Stock on a one-for-one basis upon the closing of the polls =
at the Company=E2=80=99s adjourned annual meeting of stockholders. Upon con=
version, there will be no meaningful dilution impact to Class 2 shareholder=
s from the Series A Preferred Stock, as dilution will be limited to only 0.=
0002%.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWe believe the issuance of the Series A Preferred Stock will help =
amplify and safeguard the rights of all stockholders through the approval o=
f our proposed Charter Amendment. =C2=A0This would ultimately help execute =
our strategic plan by facilitating accretive acquisitions,=E2=80=9D comment=
ed Irwin D. Simon, Tilray Brands=E2=80=99 Chairman and Chief Executive Offi=
cer. =C2=A0=E2=80=9CAn overwhelming majority of our stockholders that have =
voted at our annual meeting have voted in favor of the Charter Amendment (P=
roposal 3), but due to the nature of our stockholder base, the proposal to =
amend our Charter does not yet have enough votes to pass,=E2=80=9D Mr. Simo=
n continued. =E2=80=9CThe Series A Preferred Stock has been structured to p=
rotect stockholder interests and is an important part of our efforts to sim=
plify the Company=E2=80=99s capital structure and modernize our corporate g=
overnance with our proposed Charter Amendment.=E2=80=9D

The  buyer of the preferred stock is called Double Diamond Holdings Ltd. Ba=
sically the idea is that Tilray will give one friendly holder an extra 120 =
million votes, probably enough to pass the charter amendment, and then when=
 the vote is done that friendly holder=E2=80=99s super-voting shares will p=
oof into a smallish number of regular shares. Meanwhile the friendly holder=
 will vote exactly the same way as the actual common shareholders =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s just that the friendly holder will vote all its shares, =
while the common shareholders won=E2=80=99t. If 45% of the common votes yes=
 and 5% votes no,=C2=A0then 90% of the super-voting shares will vote yes, w=
hich will help. Tilray is issuing super-voting stock, briefly, in order to =
get rid of its super-voting stock.
This is basically Outcome 3 in my AMC scenarios: If the Tilray shareholders=
 who bother to vote vote yes, then the proposal will pass, despite not gett=
ing a majority of the outstanding common shares. Delaware law requires a ma=
jority of all common shares to vote to approve a charter amendment, and Til=
ray =E2=80=94=C2=A0like AMC =E2=80=94=C2=A0has just opted out of that requi=
rement with a weird trick. In AMC that=E2=80=99s controversial among the sh=
areholders; in Tilray I expect it won=E2=80=99t be. (Again, they keep votin=
g in favor of this stuff, to the extent they vote.) I=E2=80=99m not=C2=A0su=
re=C2=A0that means it=E2=80=99s legal =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps Delaware law m=
eans what it says, that you need a majority of all shares to approve a char=
ter amendment, and this sort of gimmick is too cute? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I=
=E2=80=99m not sure who would object.

