-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">  know</a> the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/30685506.257425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjEvYW1jLWFwZXMtaGF0ZS1hbWMtcy1hcGVzP2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDAyMjgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB8e44922b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  deal</a>. AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. had a m=
eme stock that traded up a lot even as AMC=E2=80=99s business was strugglin=
g. AMC took advantage of this dynamic to sell a lot of stock =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0so much stock, in fact, that it ran out. Its corporate charter authorize=
s 524 million common shares, and by last summer it had issued essentially a=
ll of them.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The obvious solution was for AMC to ask its sh=
areholders to vote to amend the charter and authorize more shares. In 2021,=
 AMC did that, but then withdrew the proposal in the face of shareholder =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, I am not sure what to call it. =E2=80=9CShareholder op=
position,=E2=80=9D perhaps. =E2=80=9CShareholder indifference,=E2=80=9D may=
be. The point is that AMC needed to get a vote of a majority of all of its =
common shares to approve the charter amendment. There were two problems. On=
e is that its shareholders are mostly individual retail investors, and reta=
il investors tend not to vote much<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>;=C2=A0only about half of AMC=E2=80=99s shares voted at its <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30685506.257425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTQxMTU3OS8wMDAxNTU4Mzcw=
MjIwMTAxMDAvYW1jLTIwMjIwNjE2eDhrLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2da76eee" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> last annual meeting</a>. The other is that some of those investors =
really didn=E2=80=99t like the plan to issue more stock, worrying that it w=
ould dilute their ownership (or help out short sellers, or otherwise bring =
down the price of AMC stock). Those two problems are additive: AMC needed a=
 majority of=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of its shares to vote to authorize more=
 shares; if 40% of its shareholders didn=E2=80=99t vote and another 20% vot=
ed no, then the proposal would fail. So AMC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/30685506.257425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoa=
XZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMDg5MTg2L3RtMjEyMTQ2N2Q0X2Rl=
ZmExNGEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3aee4411" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> withdrew it</a>.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last summer, AMC came up with a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30685506.257425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjMvYW1jLWdvZXMtYXBlP2N=
tcGlkPUJCRDAyMjgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZX=
dzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB7337be32" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">  less obvious but much funnier solution</=
a>: Its board used its authority to issue =E2=80=9Cblank-check preferred st=
ock=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0basically preferred stock with any terms it lik=
es, without shareholder approval =E2=80=94=C2=A0to issue a new sort of stoc=
k called APEs, AMC Preferred Equity Units, that are meant to replicate comm=
on stock. They have the same economic rights as common stock, and the same =
voting rights. AMC airdropped the APEs on its shareholders, issuing one APE=
 for each common share as a stock dividend, and then went merrily along sel=
ling APEs to raise more cash.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way for this to go would be for the market=
 to decide that APEs are a close substitute for common shares, and price th=
em accordingly. That mostly did not happen: By Dec. 21, AMC=E2=80=99s commo=
n stock was trading at $5.30 per share, while the APEs were at just $0.685.=
 AMC was selling an economic equivalent to common stock at an 80+% discount=
 to the price of the common stock, which is=C2=A0<em>definitely=C2=A0</em>d=
ilutive for shareholders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other way for it to go would be for AMC to=
 ask shareholders again to amend the charter and authorize more shares, and=
 then to use the additional authorization to convert the APEs into common s=
hares and collapse everything back into one, more abundant, class of stock.=
 On Dec. 22, AMC=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/30685506.257425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE=
0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIyMTI5MzUzL3RtMjIzMzMxOGQxX2V4OTktMS5odG0/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB745a8b11" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">announced</a>=C2=A0that it would do that. =
The APEs went up, and the common stock went down, as the market anticipated=
 that the conversion.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The shareholder vote to approve the conversion=
 is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30685506.25742=
5/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwN=
DY1OTIzMDIwNDU4L3RtMjMyNzAwLTJfZGVmMTRhLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB915d=
5e45" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> scheduled for March 14</a>. One assumes it will be approved:=
</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The APEs and common shares vote toget=
her as a single class, and there are now way more APEs than common shares.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The APEs have an incentive to vote=
 yes: If their APEs are converted into common stock, that is good for APE h=
olders, since right now APEs trade at a much lower price than the common.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A big block of APEs was placed with=
 one investor, Antara Capital LP, who agreed to hold its APEs through the v=
ote and vote them in favor of the amendment.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">The APEs have a voting mechanism where they are technically pref=
erred shares held by a depositary, and the depositary has to vote=C2=A0<em>=
all=C2=A0</em>of the shares in proportion to the voting instructions it act=
ually gets, so if 40% of APE holders vote yes and 10% vote no (and 50% don=
=E2=80=99t vote), the actual preferred shares will vote 80% yes and 20% no.=
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/30685506.257425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDEvYW1jLWhhcy1zb21lLWNsZXZlci1hcGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyM=
jgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0=
bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
C8057c698" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">  wrote</a>: =E2=80=9CAMC has <em>solved</em> the proble=
m of retail non-voting, by giving its retail shareholders APE units that (1=
) have voting rights but (2) don=E2=80=99t rely on most of the holders <em>=
actually bothering to vote</em>.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/30685506.257425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjEvYW1jLWFwZXMtaGF0ZS1hbWMtcy1hcGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRD=
AyMjgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJ=
nV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cC8e44922b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  some shareholders sued</a>, claiming that this is a=
ll not allowed, that it is a trick to get around the requirement that the b=
oard can=E2=80=99t amend the charter without the approval of a majority of =
all shares. (Which is true!) And yesterday they <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30685506.257425/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pb=
y9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JvX3BDVTU0Q1M4OC92MA/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB96727acb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> struck a deal with AMC</a>:=C2=A0</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The vote will go ahead as scheduled on=
 March 14.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">AMC will report how man=
y common shares vote for the proposal, how many vote against, how many don=
=E2=80=99t vote, etc., and also how many APEs do each of those things.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Whether or not AMC wins the vote =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0again, I expect it will win the=C2=A0<em>overall=C2=A0</em>vote=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0it will not immediately amend the charter to authorize more=
 shares; instead it will wait for a court hearing.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">They=E2=80=99ll meet back in court on April 27 to fight ov=
er whether AMC can amend the charter.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The result is that, when they go to court to d=
ecide if all of this is fair or not, they=E2=80=99ll=C2=A0<em>know what the=
 vote was</em>. Conceptually:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If everyone votes no, then AMC won=E2=
=80=99t amend the charter and the lawsuit will be irrelevant.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If a majority of all of the common shares vote =
yes, and the APEs also vote yes, then that will be a pretty strong indicati=
on that this is all fine and shareholders approve it anyway, so the lawsuit=
 will probably be irrelevant.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If a=
 majority of the common shares=C2=A0<em>that vote=C2=A0</em>vote yes, and t=
he APEs also vote yes, but the amendment fails to get a majority of=C2=A0<e=
m>all=C2=A0</em>of the common shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0if 40% of the common vo=
tes yes, 20% votes no, and 40% doesn=E2=80=99t vote at all, say =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0then in April AMC will have a decent argument to the judge to the eff=
ect of: =E2=80=9CLook, yes, we did this to get around the strict letter of =
the=C2=A0voting requirements, but as you see, even with all the publicity t=
his has generated, our shareholders never vote. So we are doing what we thi=
nk is best for them and also what a majority of them, as best we can tell, =
actually want.=E2=80=9D I am not=C2=A0<em>sure=C2=A0</em>that a judge would=
 allow the amendment, in this case, but it would be a bit harsh to stop it.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Conversely, if a majority of the =
APEs vote yes, and if that is enough for the amendment to pass, but most of=
 the=C2=A0<em>common=C2=A0</em>shareholders who vote=C2=A0<em>vote no</em>,=
 then the suing shareholders will have a decent argument to the judge of to=
 the effect of: =E2=80=9CLook, AMC did this with the intention of avoiding =
shareholder approval, and the shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0the real, common =
shareholders =E2=80=94 voted against it, but they want to do it anyway, and=
 you shouldn=E2=80=99t let them.=E2=80=9D I am not=C2=A0<em>sure=C2=A0</em>=
that a judge would stop the amendment, in this case, but it would be pretty=
 sticky.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I don=E2=80=99t know what will happen and =
the nice thing is that we=E2=80=99ll find out in March. And then if it=E2=
=80=99s Outcome 1 or Outcome 2, the lawsuit is irrelevant; if it=E2=80=99s =
Outcome 3, AMC=E2=80=99s chances in court will be pretty good; if it=E2=80=
=99s Outcome 4, AMC=E2=80=99s chances will be much worse.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way. I don=E2=80=99t know what would ha=
ve happened if AMC had actually held a vote to authorize more shares in Jul=
y 2021, when it had planned to. One possibility is that the amendment would=
 have passed, narrowly. Another is that it would have failed because most s=
hareholders would have voted against it. A third possibility =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0perhaps the most likely? =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that it would have gotten mor=
e yes votes than no votes, but not=C2=A0<em>enough=C2=A0</em>yes votes; it =
would have gotten a majority of the=C2=A0<em>votes=C2=A0</em>but not of the=
 <em>total=C2=A0shares</em>, and would fail. And if that had happened, then=
 AMC could have eventually done the APEs thing, and then it could go to a j=
udge now and say =E2=80=9Clook, our shareholders want this, but they don=E2=
=80=99t vote, so we found a way to do it for them anyway,=E2=80=9D and the =
judge might be sympathetic.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One reason I think this was the most likely ou=
tcome is because AMC clearly should have been issuing stock in July 2021, w=
hen the stock was trading in the $40s and AMC was a $20 billion company; th=
e stock closed yesterday at $7.61, for a market cap under $6 billion. Surel=
y not every AMC shareholder saw it that way =E2=80=94=C2=A0if they were buy=
ing the stock at $40 I guess they thought it was worth more =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
but, I mean, it was a really good opportunity to sell stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=C2=A0<em>now=C2=A0</em>things are differen=
t.=C2=A0<em>Now</em>, if=C2=A0you are an AMC common shareholder, you might =
reasonably vote no on this proposal:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The stock is cheaper now, so share is=
suances will be more dilutive.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In =
particular, converting the APEs into common stock will be dilutive: Antara =
bought more than <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
0685506.257425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1=
NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIyMTI5MzUzL3RtMjIzMzMxOGQxX2V4OTktMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cC745a8b11" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> 250 million APEs</a> for under $1 each, and =
would now get to convert them into common stock that=C2=A0closed yesterday =
at $7.61.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You might just be mad at=
 AMC for trying to sneak this past you.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might still reasonably vote yes! You might=
 think, well, yes, AMC does need to raise equity capital, so we=E2=80=99d b=
etter let them. You might think, well, if we don=E2=80=99t approve the amen=
dment, they=E2=80=99re going to keep issuing APEs at under $1 per share, an=
d that=E2=80=99s worse than just selling common stock. But in July 2021, it=
 would have been reasonable to say =E2=80=9Clook, our shareholders=C2=A0<em=
>should=C2=A0</em>want to authorize more shares, and they probably=C2=A0<em=
>do</em>, but they just don=E2=80=99t vote.=E2=80=9D Now that is much less =
obvious. Now they might actually vote no. Which would make AMC=E2=80=99s ar=
gument in court a lot harder.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway this deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0vote in March,=
 but wait until April for the court hearing =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems to be good=
 for the common stock price and bad for the APE price. It is particularly=
=C2=A0terrible for anyone who is in the arbitrage trade of being long the A=
PEs, short the common, and betting on convergence. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Yiqi=
n Shen and Bailey Lipshultz <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/30685506.257425/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjcvYW1jLWNvbW1vbi1zdG9jay1zb2Fycy1hcy1oZWFyaW5nLXJpc2tzLWRl=
bGF5aW5nLWFwZS1jb252ZXJzaW9uP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWR=
pdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcG=
FpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB14983ed1" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  reported =
yesterday</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. common stock s=
urged 23% after a Delaware court said it will hold a preliminary injunction=
 hearing on April 27, signaling a highly anticipated conversion between the=
 shares and preferred units may take longer than expected. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The common stock spiked to $7.61 while APE sha=
res slipped to $2.05. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe preliminary injunction hearing on=
 April 27 extends the time that investors have to hold long APE/short AMC b=
y at least a month and a half, given the horrifically high cost of borrow t=
his is a painful outcome for arbitragers,=E2=80=9D said Cabot Henderson, wh=
o focuses on merger arbitrage and special situations at JonesTrading.</p>
</blockquote>
